# Role Descriptions: Project Manager (PM) & Project Director (PD)

## High-Level Overview

| Role | Core Purpose | Accountability & Leadership |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Project Manager (PM) | Responsible for the successful delivery of projects, ensuring they are completed on time, within budget, and to required quality standards. | An active management role that upholds company reputation, ensures H&S compliance, and develops the team through coaching. Has primary responsibility for commercial hygiene from start to completion. |
| Project Director (PD) | Accountable for successful project delivery by providing strategic oversight and managing risk, quality, and commercial performance. | Upholds reputation by aligning delivery with client expectations and company values. Has overall accountability for the team's Health, Safety, and Wellbeing (HSW) and coaches the PM. |

## Project Manager (PM)

### Qualifications

- You are appointed as a Project Manager for the company.

### Working Relationships

- Clients (and/or their representatives)
- Discipline Director / Practice Lead (accountable for PM performance)
- Project Team (e.g., Project Director, Project Manager in Training (PMIT), Project Controller / BIS, technical staff, Technical reviewers, Third-party suppliers)
- Project Support (e.g., Client Manager, Risk Assessment Task Group (RAT), Project Assistance Team (PAT), Legal, HSW, and Commercial teams)

### Expectations, Responsibilities, & Accountabilities

- Client Management: Build strong client relationships by understanding their needs, communicating clearly, being responsive, and proactively managing risks and opportunities.
- Communication: Maintain clear, consistent communication with the project team and stakeholders to manage expectations, ensure transparency, and support successful project delivery.
- Project Proposals: Develop project proposals that clearly define scope, deliverables, timelines, resource needs, and budget estimates, tailored to meet the needs of the client.
- Health & Safety (HSW): Embed health and safety considerations into all phases of the project, from planning through to delivery, and ensure the health, safety, and wellbeing of the project team is prioritized.
- Contract Management: Ensure contractual obligations are understood, tracked, and met through the project lifecycle.
- Project Delivery: Apply a structured, proactive approach using a Project Management Plan (PMP) to guide delivery. Drive successful project outcomes by proactively managing scope, budget, programme, communications, risks, opportunities, and maintaining up-to-date financials (commercial hygiene).
- Change Control: Manage scope, budget, and schedule changes through proactive change control and variation management processes.
- Quality Assurance: Ensure deliverables meet project objectives and have appropriate quality and technical review.
- Compliance: Comply with the Six Key Business Rules and company policies relevant to project management throughout the lifecycle.
- Team Leadership: Provide support and coaching to the PMIT and project team by being responsive and proactive to their needs.
- Professional Development: Continuously develop your project management skills through training, forums, and hands-on experience.

### Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

- High client satisfaction scores/feedback.
- Delivery to scope, programme, and budget.
- Technical and/or oversight review completed for every deliverable.
- HSW requirements are met (e.g., JSEA/SCAN completed, Health and Safety by Design).
- Good commercial hygiene (e.g., up-to-date financials and Project Management Plan for every project).
- Retention and feedback from the project team.

## Project Director (PD)

### Qualifications

- You are appointed as a Project Director for the company.

### Working Relationships

- Clients (and/or their representatives)
- Discipline Director / Practice Lead (accountable for PD performance)
- Project Team (e.g., Project Manager (or PMIT where appropriate), Project Controller / BIS, Technical reviewers)
- Project Support (e.g., Client Manager, Risk Assessment Task Group (RAT), Project Assistance Team (PAT), Legal, HSW, and Commercial teams)

### Expectations, Responsibilities, & Accountabilities

- Client Alignment: Help incorporate the client’s perspective into our deliverables to ensure they align with their expectations and needs, and maintain strong, responsive client relationships.
- Commercial Oversight: Ensure there is a commercially acceptable contract in place for every engagement and variation, unless an exception has been formally approved.
- Project Governance: Ensure projects are set up for success, risks are identified and managed, and that there is an appropriate PMP in place for every project. Ensure strong financial performance of your projects.
- Quality Assurance: Ensure deliverables meet project objectives and quality standards through appropriate technical oversight and review.
- Compliance: Ensure that the project team complies with the Six Key Business Rules and company policies relevant to project management throughout the project lifecycle.
- Health & Safety (HSW): Ensure health and safety have been considered for all phases of the project, from planning through to delivery, and ensure the health, safety, and wellbeing of the project team is prioritized.
- Project Oversight: Maintain oversight of project performance, risk management, and delivery to ensure the project delivers to scope, on time, and to budget. This includes meeting the PM regularly (at least monthly) to review and discuss project performance.
- Leadership & Coaching: Provide support and coaching to the PM (or PMIT where relevant) by being responsive and proactive to their needs.
- Professional Development: Continuously develop your project director skills through training, forums, and hands-on experience.

### Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

- High client satisfaction scores/feedback.
- Commercially acceptable contract for every client/supplier engagement and variation.
- Deliverables are fit for purpose, meet quality/technical standards, and align with client expectations (minimizing rework).
- Strong project financial performance.
- PMP in place (including effective risk management strategies) for every project.
- Retention and feedback from Project Managers.
